Assess a menu for 1 cycle to determine the extent to which made from scratch or almost scratch entrées are
For each day of the cycle and for each entrée ask the kitchen manager or CND to describe the preparation
method using one of the 4 definitions. Please provide an explanation if a day is left incomplete.
Convenience means the foods are fully processed and only require heating and serving. Examples include heat-
in-serve macaroni and cheese and premade bean and cheese burrito.
Minimal preparation means assembly of ingredients that are highly processed. Examples include premade
meatloaf with rehydrated mashed potatoes and chili dogs make with hot dogs and school made-chili.
Fast scratch means some of the ingredients are raw and some mixing, cooking and preparation is involved. An
example is chicken teriyaki made with precooked and sauced chicken strips, fresh rice and fresh vegetables.
Made from scratch means the ingredients are raw or close-to-raw, including unseasoned, pre-cooked meat. An
example is chicken fajitas made with grilled chicken strips, tortillas and fresh vegetables.
For each of the preparation methods record the corresponding number:
